		<h1>Our Idea</h1>


		<h3>Goal</h3>
		
		<p>Our goal with StudyBuddy is to make the process of arranging effective group study sessions effortless and to encourage students to participate in group studies. We want to see students collaborating with one another.</p>
		
		<h3>Why?</h3>
		<p>Because we think that if done in a certain way, group studying can be a very effective way of learning. We think collaboration among students ignites creativity and new ideas. Please view the <a href = "http://www.ted.com/talks/howard_rheingold_on_collaboration.html" target="_blank">Power of collaboration</a> Ted Talk if you want to find out more.</p> 
		<p>Moreover, we think are lots of complications in arranging an effective group study sessions. These complications might even discourage students from taking advantage of the benefits that come from studying in groups.</p>

		<h3>What might be those complications?</h3>
	<ul>
		<b><li>Scheduling Problems</li></b>
		<p>It is difficult to find a common time between more than two students. Reaching out to more than one person to arrange a common time can take a lot of time and effort.</p>
		<b><li>Mutuality</li></b>
		<p>The best study sessions are when students in the groups have similar goals. There might be situations where you only need to solve one more problem in the problem set, whereas your friends have not started the homework yet. This applies not only to problem sets, but other assignments as well.</p>
		<b><li>No existing friends in the class</li></b>
		<p>Students are more likely to study in groups if they already have friends who are also enrolled in the class. However, there might be situations in which you might not know your fellow classmates. In these situations, it might be more difficult to reach out to an unfamiliar classmate.</p>
	</ul>

