	<h3>How is StudyBuddy different from other mediums of forming group study?</h3>
	<ul>
		<b><li>Texting, emailing, Facebook message and in-person</li></b>
		<p>Scheduling needs to be done through continuous communication. The back and forth nature of this might require a lot of time and effort, especially if you are trying to arrange group study with more than one friend. In StudyBuddy you will be able to arrange a group study session effortlessly in communicating with your friends.</p>
		<p>In addition, you need to have your classmate's number, be Facebook friends or know the person in order to extend a conventional study group invitation.  However, with StudyBuddy you can invite all of your classmates that have registered on the website.</p>
		<p>Finally, it's hard to select the right audience with these methods. If a classmate is your Facebook friend or you have their number/email, it doesnâ€™t necessarily mean that he/she wants to study in a group. However, all students who register for StudyBuddy are those who would be interested in studying in groups.</p>
		<p>In short, using Study Buddy is an easier way to reach out to classmates who are interested in studying in groups. It is a much easier process than the more conventional trial and error methods of texting, emailing and even in-person.</p>
		<b><li>Facebook Events</li></b>
		<p>While creating Facebook events for your study sessions may be a good idea, it is only effective if you are Facebook friends with your classmates. Moreover, there is no way to tell if the friends that you invited are free and willing to study at any given date and time.  StudyBuddy, on the contrary, allows you to update your timing preferences and recommends times that are most likely going to work for your classmates.  It is simply an easier way to reach out to your classmates, as well as to easily determine which times might work best for all participants.</p>
		<b><li>LATTE Forum Posts</li></b>
		<p>In general, LATTE forum posts are sent to everyone in class through emails. Naturally, this entails some of the complications mentioned in the first bullet point.  In all honesty, nobody wants extra emails, and thus this method is largely ineffective.</p>
	</ul>

